```Additionally, an empty array is returned when the starting index for an element range is at the end of the array.

Raises IndexError if the starting index is out of range.```

```
a = ["a", "b", "c", "d", "e"]
a[6, 1]  # raise IndexError
a[5, 1]  # => [] # Empty Array```
Ini menjawab yang dulu kenapa a[5] error, tapi a[5,1] engga.
Starting indexnya jika pakai count dihitung dari array sizenya bukan posisi element dari index 0.
Dan masuk akal kenapa begitu karena starting index bisa negative: indexnya start dari -1 bukan 0. Sehingga posisi element terakhir jika reverse adalah -5, seolah-olah index terakhir adalah 5.

Analogy REST vs GraphQL

```For example, I want a banana.

Using GraphQL is like asking for a banana and actually getting a banana, instead of asking for a banana then getting the banana but with a gorilla holding it -- along with the whole forest.

With GraphQL, you also don't care where the banana comes from as long as you get it.```
